Part I - Environmental & Social Factors of Industrialization from 1990-2019.¶

by Catherine Taft¶

Introduction¶

I'm working with a dataset that I created from combining several smaller ones to examine the growth and industrialization of countries, essentially. I started out just looking at CO2 emissions, but needed to expand my dataset significantly in order to fulfill the variable requirements of this project, so I looked for other datasets that reflected factors of economic development, and so my combined dataset will incorporate the following (datasets will be specifically referenced and linked at the bottom of the notebook):

  1. CO2 Emissions (Source: Kaggle via World Bank)
  2. Child Mortality; 0-5 Year Olds Dying per 1000 Born (Source: Gapminder)
  3. Income Per Person/GDP Per Capita; Inflation-Adjusted (Source: Gapminder)
  4. Life Expectancy in Years (Source: Gapminder)
  5. Population Density per Square Km (Source: Gapminder)

Preliminary Wrangling¶

I did most of the data cleaning in Excel due to the small size of the source datasets (around 200 rows each before the required melts). I standardized numerical formats (some had for example 31k instead of 31000) and trimmed the data to the same range of years and the same countries. Here I will be performing melts, renaming a few things, and combining them into a final single dataframe.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The end result of all that merging is a dataframe with 8 columns and 5400 rows. There are 180 countries represented in this dataset, which is nearly all of the countries in the world. Most of the ones removed were either territories (i.e. Macao, Puerto Rico) or extremely small island nations (i.e. Vanuatu) that didn't have any data. The 2 categorical variables are country name and region, there's year (not sure how you'd classify that), and then the remaining 5 are quantitative variables for emissions per capita, child mortality rate, income rate, life expectancy and population density.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

These are all variables that I think could have some level of interaction. My initial desire was to look at emission rates globally, but now we can look at how for example child mortality rates and life expectancy correlate with emission rates; in developing countries, an increase in emissions often indicates an increase in industrialization and therefore an overall increase in wealth, which should result in lower infant mortality and higher life expectancy, but pollution adversely affects both. As a lifelong urbanite I'm also curious to see how population density relates to these other variables.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I'm not really sure what this question means. I imagine that the numeric values will speak for themselves and by doing some visualizations it will be pretty clear. I do expect to see positive correlations between emissions and things like income, population density etc but there may be some surprises when it comes to the strength of the correlation in many of these cases.

The first thing I want to do since it was my initial subject of interest, is look specifically at emissions and see how the various regions compare. The plot I would be inclined to do first is bivariate so I've had to stick it at the front of the next section. Here I can do some pie charts though to see the proportions of emissions each region is responsible for. Let's first look at the emissions in 1990, and then in 2019.

In [526]:
emissions = industrialization_data[['country_name', 'region', 'year', 'emissions_per_cap']]
nineties_emissions = emissions.loc[emissions['year'] == '1990']
nineties_emissions.groupby(['region']).sum().plot(kind='pie', y= 'emissions_per_cap', legend = None)
plt.title('Regional Emissions in 1990');
In [527]:
nineties_emissions = emissions.loc[emissions['year'] == '2019']
nineties_emissions.groupby(['region']).sum().plot(kind='pie', y= 'emissions_per_cap', legend = None)
plt.title('Regional Emissions in 2019');

The change we see across these are interesting. There is a marked decrease in Europe & Central Asia, which tracks with some foreign policy decisions in Europe in the 2000s around nuclear energy and other renewables, as well as a significant increase in LATAM, Sub-Sararan Africa and South Asia. As I mentioned as countries industrialize more they have a higher higher consumption of fossil fuels and therefore more carbon emissions. This is surely the case in LATAM, and India emerging in the past decade or so could account for the increase in South Asia.

Next I'd like to look at how the other variables (child mortality, income, life expectancy, population density) looked in 1990, and then in the bivariate section I'll do some clustered charts to see how they compare between the start and end of the dataset. Honestly having to segment this into categories of variate-ness is a little disorienting in terms of presenting a narrative.

In [528]:
#function for bar charts to reduce repetitive code

def unibar(plotdata, ydata, x_label, y_label, plot_title):
    plotdata.groupby(['region']).mean().plot(kind='bar', y= ydata, legend = None)
    plt.title(plot_title, fontsize = 17)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 17)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 17)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 45);
In [529]:
#child mortality
nineties = industrialization_data.loc[industrialization_data['year'] == '1990']
child_mort_nineties = nineties[['region', 'child_mort_rate']]

unibar(child_mort_nineties, 'child_mort_rate', 'Region', 'Child Mortality Rate', 'Child Mortality Rates Across Regions in 1990')
In [ ]:

This is actually pretty stunning. It makes sense that The US and Canada have comparatively low child mortality rates in 1990, as so many countries have developed significantly since then, but the high child mortality rates in South Asia and Sub Saharan Africa are breathtaking. Let's look at life expectancy and see how that compares.

In [530]:
#life expectancy
nineties_life = nineties[['region', 'life_expectancy']]

unibar(nineties_life, 'life_expectancy', 'Region', 'Life Expectancy', 'Life Expectancy Across Regions in 1990')

Here I plotted the mean life expectancy for each region. We still see North America as coming out on top, and there's a difference of around 20 years between North America and Sub Saharan Africa, which is significant, and South Asia is not much better. Keep in mind that life expectancy data is usually affected by child mortality rates. Consider the trope that adults in the Middle Ages only lived to be 40ish - that's not true, if they reached adulthood they usually lived to their 70s or later like everyone else. The numbers were skewed by an extraordinary infant mortality rate due to lack of medical care/knowledge and sanitation, among other things.

Next we'll look at GDP per person.

In [531]:
#GDP per capita
nineties_income = nineties[['region', 'income_per_person']]

unibar(nineties_income, 'income_per_person', 'Region', 'Life Expectancy', 'GDP per Capita Across Regions in 1990')

To me the main surprise here is the disparity between Europe and North America, but Europe's mean may be brought down a bit by Central Asia, and in 1990 right at the very end of the USSR a lot of Eastern Europe was very impoverished and in social disarray. The Middle East being nearly on par (comparatively) with Europe is also a bit surprising but I assume that has to do with oil-producing nations being located there.

The last one we'll look at here is population density. I'm more interested in that as a variable to compare to others rather than as a standalone, but since we're introducing variables here we might as well look at it.

In [532]:
#life expectancy
nineties_pop = nineties[['region', 'population_density']]

unibar(nineties_pop, 'population_density', 'Region', 'Life Expectancy', 'Avg Population Density Across Regions in 1990')

This is a little surprising but I think it's because of the categories used in these datasets. South Asia and East Asia make sense (China and India are enormous countries that currently make up over 35% of the global population) but I think it's interesting that the Middle East and North Africa are so high above North America. This may be due to the fact that North Africa has some really populous countries (Algeria, Sudan, Egypt) and the North American category only contains two countries, one of whom (Canada) is mostly uninhabitable due to being mostly in the arctic circle, and the US's most populous city, New York, is smaller than your average city in China. Fun fact: 90% of Canada is uninhabited and in 2022 the entire national population is about the same as the population of California. So in terms of number of people packed into spaces, due to how this data is segmented, this makes sense.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I did not need to perform any transformations. The distributions all made sense upon considering them, although the visualizations did produce some results that surprised me upon first seeing them, which I outlined below the individual charts. I do think some of the surprises (like North America's low placement with population distribution) is due to how the data is segmented, as I mentioned. But in general, when placed in the context of regional development in 1990 (and in the case of the pie charts, development over time) the distributions are logical.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The only thing that gave me pause was that the category of North America only included two countries. In reality it also includes Mexico, the Caribbean, and Central America, and the exclusion of Mexico in particular, a large and populous country with a diverse and successful manufacturing industry, impacts North America's data obviously. However I chose to leave it is it is because the data had been segmented to separate out the Caribbean and Latin America (which obviously includes Mexico and Central America), and when considering indeces of development, it makes a lot of sense to do that, as these regions have a lot of cultural and political commonalities or relationships that impact development and are deeper than the sort of arbitrary designation of "North America." So I left that, and nothing else required change or tidying.

The US is predictably up there on the top, and Sub-Saharan Africa is predictably down there at the bottom. The Middle East's presence in the solid middle intrigued me so I looked into this. You'd think that it would be due to their role as the world's major oil producers, but it's actually because of their enormous population growth coupled with a massive energy need (and the financial ability to provide this energy infrastructure due to oil wealth) due to the extremely hot climate (Kouyakhi, 2022). The huge decrease in Europe tracks - recall the large decrease in proportion of emissions in the pie charts.

There is a fairly sharp increase followed by a decrease over the span of about 2.5 years in Latin America & Caribbean that is pretty interesting. Below I did some queries and it looks like the culprit is the Caribbean. In that period we see some really high emissions values from Antigua, Bahamas, Barbados, and Trinidad. I looked into this and according to a paper from the UN written around that time, Trinidad is actually a major oil producer and petrochemicals are produced throughout the Caribbean (UN, 2011). Energy consumption is also a factor.

I also found it a bit surprising that East Asia was towards the bottom given the level of pollution China puts out, but again it is likely due to low emitters being grouped in with them in that regional designation. I would actually like to look at the US and China together.

So there is a lot of really interesting information here. First, we see that the US has a very high carbon emissions rate, which peaks around the year 2000 and starts to decline rather sharply. Note though that in 2019 at its lowest point in this dataset it was at 15 metric tons per capita which is still a lot. China, meanwhile, begins a sharp increase around 2000 as the country began to rapidly industrialize. They did more or less level off in the early 2010s, and while they still emit a ton of carbon, it's not that easy to just move an enormous industrial economy and an energy grid that caters to over a billion people off of fossil fuels. They are beginning to invest heavily in renewable technology like solar power. It's worth noting that their peak is about half of where the US ended up after their decline.

I had thought China's emissions would have pulled East Asia's grouping up significantly among the rest, similar to how their population density pulled the region up, but it turns out that their emissions are just nowhere near what the US's are (and Canada is also a fairly high emitter given its small population), while China has a large number of megacities (cities with a population over 10 million) and quite a few that are approaching that mark, so they are simply contributing more to the population density factor.

There's a lot of good stuff here. Let's go in order from bottom up on the Y axis.

  1. Population density - Some obvious ones: the lower the density, the lower the emissions, lower income in areas of lower population density. A bit of a tendency towards lower child mortality as the density increases, but not significant. Similarly a bit of an increase in life expectancy as density increases, but I think both of these could be attributed to easier access to medical care and other resources.

  2. Life expectancy - an exponential positive correlation with both emissions and income, but with emissions the majority is towards the lower emissions end. Increased emissions indicate industrial development which will influence these other factors that positively influence life expectancy, but the majority of emissions is simply within a certain bracket. The strong negative correlation between child mortality and life expectancy is obvious.

  3. Child mortality - With emissions we can see at a low emissions rate the data spans the range of child mortality levels, but in general there is a slight clumping towards very low emissions/low child mortality, which is very interesting. I would have expected the opposite, to be honest.

  4. Income - a somewhat weak but distinct positive correlation with emissions, which makes sense, and kind of a range on life expectancy.

  5. Emissions - the last one that hasn't been mentioned is the exponential relationship to life expectancy, which also makes sense when we consider that as countries develop, life expectancy will go up for a variety of reasons.

# function for paired bar charts to reduce repetitive code

def pairbar(plotdata, x_label, y_label, plot_title):
    plotdata.mean().unstack('year').plot(kind = 'bar')
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 17)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 17)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
    plt.title(plot_title, fontsize = 17)
    plt.show()

# function for violin plots

def violinpl(plotdata, xdata, ydata, x_label, y_label, plot_title):
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(25, 8))
    sns.violinplot(x=xdata, y=ydata, hue='year', data=plotdata)

    f.suptitle(plot_title, fontsize=17)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 17)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 17)
    #plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

The density of the data points is also far less clustered around the median in all cases. All of this, in both plots, can be read as a widespread increase in wealth inequality.

#function for multivariate scatterplots

def fancyscatter(plotdata, xdata, ydata, sdata, x_label, y_label, plot_title):
    g = sns.FacetGrid(data=plotdata, hue= 'region', height = 10)
    g.map_dataframe(sns.regplot, xdata, ydata, scatter=False)
    g.map_dataframe(sns.scatterplot, xdata, ydata, size= sdata, marker='o')
    g.add_legend()
    plt.title(plot_title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label);
In [376]:
fancyscatter(plot1, 'income_per_person', 'emissions_per_cap', 'life_expectancy', 'GDP Per Capita', 'Emissions Per Capita','Emissions against GDP per Capita, Size as Life Expectancy')

There isn't a lot of variation in life expectancy but we do see a trend from lower life expectancy along the low end of GDP, to a higher life expectancy on the high end. The trajectory of the Middle East is very clear, positively correlated with increases in both GDP and emissions. Europe is bunched down with low to middle/high income with some outliers on the X axis, and low/moderate emissions. East Asia & Pacific has some different groupings resembling what we saw earlier. With some exceptions in the Middle East, we don't really see any low life expectancies at higher GDP levels, and all the life expectancies at low/moderate emissions levels and medium/high income levels are high.

Conclusions¶

This was a pretty interesting exploration for me as someone with an interest in this topic. Just a reminder, I looked at child mortality rate, life expectancy, GDP per capita, CO2 emissions rate, and population density, for various regions and countries, between the years of 1990 and 2019. A lot of this confirmed general knowledge like that the US/Canada and Europe are reducing carbon emissions but most of the developing world is increasing in emissions due to the nature of development as we currently know it. We also saw a general increase in life expectancy and decrease in child mortality, which is also common knowledge.

One of the really stunning findings for me, which is not surprising as a fact as much as it was kind of alarming to see it visually, was the depiction of steadily and substantially increasing wealth inequality across all regions of the world. I actually sent those two plots to several of my friends after making them because I was so taken aback.

It was also interesting to me to see a couple of variables that didn't really make sense in a bivariate setting (population density, child mortality) come to life as third variables in a multivariate setting. I really would like to do some regression analyses at a later time to get more information about how these variables all interact, but I will leave that for another time.
